Interactive kiosks are self-contained computing 
terminals that provide access to on-demand 
information and transactions. Some examples 
include airport self-check-in systems, retail 
product locators, and bill pay terminals. 
Interactive kiosks typically utilize a touch 
screen for data entry, along with an on-screen 
keyboard and other peripherals, such as card 
readers and barcode scanners. A thermal printer 
is the most common output device. Some interactive 
kiosks are even equipped to burn custom CDs or 
DVDs on demand, or download multimedia files to 
handheld media players. Interactive kiosks may 
have a customized, hardened enclosure, or may 
simply be a standard PC that has been repurposed 
for interactive kiosk duties.
